\maketitle

\section{Introduction}
As students, being able to learn something new efficiently and effectively is critical for success in school. The mediums used by teachers have remained relatively unaltered for many years, as these methods have been proven to work for most students. Although learning has been associated with the traditional teaching method of teachers giving students information through lectures and PowerPoint presentations, much research has been done to learn more about how the human brain learns new information \cite{Kolb01}. However, just because something works, does not mean it cannot be further developed \cite{Adcock08}\cite{Hooper11}. Technology has gone through rapid evolution in the past 100 years, presenting an increasing number of tools that educators can use \cite{Oleson14}. A great example of this happened during the recent COVID-19 pandemic, with a large percentage of students using online methods for learning. Studies have suggested these methods have proved to be more effective as a teaching medium over classical methods, however, students still prefer learning in a physical classroom \cite{Karamazova21}.

Video games are just one of the most recent developments, with a growing number of younger generations adopting them into their lives. It has been found that some video games can create a basis upon which students can expand and learn new information more effectively than others who haven’t played video games \cite{Arena15}. Using an interactive educational medium to teach allows students to have more fun learning the information \cite{COLLER09} and could be more effective than traditional teaching methods \cite{Arena15}. With further research, there can be many new ways of teaching and presenting new information to modern students.


\section{Related Works}
Education is a controversial field of research, as is most of human psychology, as not enough information is definitively known. But education does not reside fully in psychology, rather it can involve other theoretical approaches, such as sociology, ethics, and history. With all these moving parts, determining what is known versus unknown presents its own problems. Much of the research that is conducted is very specific, often so specific that forming conclusions is difficult. Generalizing research can lead to forming false conclusions, which in the world of research for education happens frequently \cite{Smeyers12}. Conclusions are based on current knowledge, which is subject to change. Things such as bias and the methodology of the studies play a large role in determining if the conclusion is valid for different situations \cite{PLoS05}. Such an example is the myth of ‘learning styles’, such as 'kinesthetic' and 'visual', which is still believed to be an effective teaching method \cite{Reynolds21}.

Most preconceived notions have an element of truth involved, but determining what is fact and fiction is the hardest part of interpreting results from studies. Not everything is entirely factual, but proper use of the scientific method helps determine if something is repeatable in a controlled environment. One such study compared the different Kolb learning styles to determine which had any effect on learning results \cite{Compton16}. Similar studies were conducted to determine if being taught in one's preferred learning style has an impact on stronger learning \cite{Lu16}. 

Learning styles suggest students have different needs and to get the most effective learning, teachers must take these differences into account. This is a concept supported by research, as students come from different backgrounds, be it previous experiences or even genetic differences. However, it is important to note that while individuals may have different preferred learning styles, there is no evidence to suggest that one style leads to better or faster learning outcomes. Instead, a favorite mode of presentation (visual, auditory, or kinesthetic) for a student is a preference for tasks that an individual has a higher aptitude for rather than a learning style \cite{Riener10}. 

The notion of learning styles is one of many myths formed around education, and it will not be the last. When applied to games, many myths form obstacles in determining the relationship between video games and education. One such myth is students can readily transfer learning from games to understanding in the classroom. This would be very convenient but it cannot be assumed to be true, as just one method cannot guarantee successful learning. Rather, video games would need to be integrated into other teaching practices to facilitate improved learning and understanding \cite{McTigue18}. Video games work with inert knowledge, which is context-based. This means students will have trouble moving something that they know from a game to a different situation, such as applying skills learned from games in the real world \cite{Renkl96}. 

Interactive educational mediums cannot fully replace other forms of learning in classrooms, as education is far too broad of a subject for one method alone. Without the aid of teacher intervention, video games would not be able to find a balance for each student’s learning path \cite{Silver04}. Video games are limited by their inability to adapt to the needs of students. When students fall behind, a teacher can alter the course load to ensure they get the most out of the information being taught \cite{Berg98}. What determines the effectiveness of an interactive medium in education is the nature of the software, the influence of the teacher, the time and effort put in by the student, and the other methods that are integrated \cite{Cheung13}\cite{Kocaleva15}\cite{meral19}\cite{Wang03}. Also, the information being graded is still graded in the traditional way, meaning any un-traditional learning methods have to overcome this gap \cite{Barone08}. In other words, there are many factors that influence the effectiveness of video games as an educational medium.

There are many factors to consider when evaluating the potential of video games as an effective teaching tool. Balancing entertainment value with educational content is crucial, as an excessively dry game may lead to the target audience becoming disengaged, thus hampering their ability to retain the information presented. A larger focus on the entertainment factor means the game will be less targeted towards learning, resulting in a decrease in information learned \cite{Giannakas18}\cite{Baltra90}. Since the goal of the game is to promote learning, the way the audience feels about the software changes \cite{Vogel06}\cite{Tallim04}. If users feel they are learning from the game, they are more willing to overlook any downsides in aesthetics or functionalities\cite{Imam22}. This is one of the major issues with research involving determining the effectiveness of interactive educational mediums, as the most popular ways involve qualitative research. This presents much variability and makes it difficult to determine what is effective or what is perceived as effective \cite{Bodnar16}.

\section{Methods}

\subsection{Methodology}

This study was run as a between-subjects (i.e. non-repeated measures) experimental study. The goal of this experiment was to gain a better understanding of the learning process in an interactive, educational medium. Specifically, this study aimed to compare the effectiveness of an interactive map game \textit{Geopursuit} which was developed solely for this experiment. Participants were split into two groups, Group 1 and Group 2, with a total of 20 participants randomly assigned. Members of Group 1 were given access to the interactive map game \textit{GeoPursuit}. \textit{GeoPursuit} had users interact with a map of the continent Africa, allowing them to drag their cursor around the map to display information about the currently selected country. Group 1 was introduced to this game and given a set amount of time to become familiar with the software. Once each participant was ready, a 15-minute timer began for users to begin studying the countries of Africa using \textit{GeoPursuit}. 

\begin{figure}[h]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[scale=0.15]{africa.png}
    \caption{Top: the initial game given to Group 1, Bottom: ending of the game to reinforce skills learned}
    \label{fig:my_label1}
\end{figure}


Group 2 did not have access to \textit{GeoPursuit}, in its place they were provided a video presentation on the countries of Africa. This presentation consisted of slides of text and images along with a recorded voice-over. The presentation provided context and learning devices for learning the names of countries in Africa. The video shown to Group 2 was approximately 15 minutes long.

After 15 minutes passed, the procedure for both Group 1 and Group 2 were identical. Participants were instructed to take a five-minute break, after which the participants began a quiz. The quiz consisted of ten randomly chosen countries from Africa, where participants had to choose the correct name from a drop-down of potential countries. The participants only saw the silhouette of the country, with no other additional information. After 10 minutes, the quiz period ended and the score for each participant was calculated.

\begin{figure}[h]
    \centering
    \includegraphics{fig1.PNG}
    \caption{the quiz given to both Group 1 and Group 2}
    \label{fig:my_label2}
\end{figure}

\subsection{Participants}
The experiment was conducted with a total of 20 volunteer participants (10 Male, 10 Female). Most participants were students who were recruited from the course CS 464 and a small number were not enrolled in CS 464 and had no previous knowledge of African countries.

\subsection{Procedure}
For each session, participants started by signing the informed consent and were informed of the methodology of the experiment as well as an explanation of the research questions we hoped to answer. During the initial practice time for Group 1, participants were able to ask any questions about the layout and functions of \textit{GeoPursuit}. Participants were alerted to the tools and methods provided by the software.

\begin{figure}[h]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[scale=0.15]{test_your_knowledge.png}
    \caption{exercise for Group 1's learning period}
    \label{fig:my_label2}
\end{figure}

Once the learning period for both groups was concluded, the quiz was given to each participant. No questions could be answered relating to the content of the quiz. After the time allotted for the quiz was concluded, any question that was left unanswered was marked as incorrect. Participants were then given a questionnaire consisting of questions about their expectations of their performance on the quiz and how much they learned from their treatment.

Another session was scheduled for each participant to determine their knowledge retention after the initial experiment. Participants were given a similar quiz a small number of days after the initial experiment, the results of which were recorded.

\section{Results}
The information collected from each participant was the accuracy of their test scores, their rating of the method on a scale from 1-10, the time it took to take the test, and the number of questions the participants answered as "I don't know", which will be referred to as a non-response. From these measurements, Group 1 had an average correct score of 26.05\%. Group 2 had a higher percentage of correct answers, with an average of 35.29\%.

