An Analysis of Variance test was used to determine if the variance between the two groups' correct scores was significant. This test resulted in an F=1.1658 and a p-value=0.294521. Since our p-value is greater than our significance level of 0.05, we fail to reject the null hypothesis that there is a difference between group 1's scores and group 2's scores. The only ANOVA test that was significant was the method rating, with Group 2 having a higher method rating average than Group 1.

\begin{figure}
    \centering
    \includegraphics[scale=0.4]{Average Correct Answers for Group 1 and Group 2.png}
    \caption{Percentage for correct answers for both groups}
    \label{fig:my_label3}
\end{figure}

In terms of time taken to complete the test, Group 1 had a higher average of time taken, with an average time of 269.71 seconds. Group 2 had an average time of 248.83 seconds.

\begin{figure}[h]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[scale=0.4]{Average Time Taken For Group 1 and Group 2.png}
    \caption{Average time in seconds that each group took to finish the test}
    \label{fig:my_label4}
\end{figure}

The individual ratings for how well each participant felt the method used helped teach them provided similar results. Group 1 had an average rating of 3/10, while Group 2 had an average rating of 4.5/10.

\begin{figure}[h]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[scale=0.4]{Average Group Rating for Method.png}
    \caption{Average rating of the method given to each group out of a possible score of 10}
    \label{fig:my_label5}
\end{figure}

\section{Discussion}
The results shown above indicate the null hypothesis was not rejected. Group 1 was given the interactive map game, with the hypothesis being the participants would score higher on the test and feel more confident in the material being taught. This was not the case, as Group 1 had lower scores on the test and gave lower ratings on the effectiveness of their instructional method than the alternative method of Group 2.

While several participants in Group 2 noted that the video was difficult to concentrate on due to its length, the participants had an overall higher average score and personal ratings. In fact, Group 2 participants took less time and also had less doubt in their work, evidenced by the lower average of questions marked as "I don't know".

Some possible explanations for these disparities could be related to the way each group was instructed to learn the material. In Group 2's video, all the information was explicitly described and the participants were instructed to absorb the material to the best of their ability. In contrast, in Group 1, the information is presented to the participant, but they must actively interact with it to facilitate learning. As a result, the amount of information retained depended on the individual and the effort they put into interacting with the map game. Not to mention that learning in general is a social process, as interacting with others can help the learning process and develop stronger connections between material \cite{Lilly07}\cite{Rozalind04}. 

Some ways to combat this could be giving the participants in Group 1 a concrete goal to achieve, such as earning a certain amount of points or correct guesses by the end of their session. The current version of the game lacks a clear learning objective or structure, which may limit users' motivation to engage with the material. Therefore, incorporating a more defined learning goal or structure could potentially enhance users' learning experience and improve learning outcomes.

 

\section{Limitations of the Study}
This study has many limitations that prevented any clear conclusions. The sample size and selection of participants limited any definitive conclusions that could be gathered, as the majority of this experiment's participants were from the class of CS 464, meaning a very narrow selection that presents sample bias. The restricted sample size for this study resulted in the inability to identify any significant relationships in the data. To overcome these limitations, future studies may need to increase the sample size and diversify the participant pool to reduce sample bias and improve the ability to identify significant relationships in the data.

This experiment was unique in its approach to understanding the relationship between interactive games and learning, meaning few studies were directly relevant. This presents literature gaps and demonstrates the need for more development in this field of study. Time constraints, limited sampling, and other restricting factors mentioned previously had a large impact on the limitations of this study. There is a need for future studies on this topic to reach an informed conclusion supported by large amounts of data.

\section{Conclusions}
Given the ratings for both Groups, it is clear there is room for improvement in the teaching methods of each of these groups. Both groups had a low personal effectiveness rating for the two methods provided, along with a relatively low accuracy of answers on the test. Participants did gain relatively higher scores and gave higher effectiveness ratings with a simple PowerPoint presentation, but that does not mean that this is always the case. There are many ways to improve the interactive game to promote stronger learning, such as by giving users goals and objectives or making users follow a stricter rule set. 

The PowerPoint video is an effective baseline for a method of teaching in a classroom setting, but there is a myriad of improvements that can be applied to this study to more accurately determine several successful teaching strategies. Future studies are needed to determine these improvements and possible opportunities for improving learning rates in educational environments.

